{"title_page": "Makoti Khawula", "text_new": "{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Makoti Khawula\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Parliament of South Africa|MP]]\n| image               = Makoti Khawula sworn in.png\n| image_size          = \n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Khawula at her swearing-in in May 2019\n| office              = Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]\n| status              = \n| term_start          = 21 May 2014\n| term_end            = \n| constituency        = [[KwaZulu-Natal]]\n| birthname           = Makoti Sibongile Khawula<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\">{{cite web |title=Ms Makoti Sibongile Khawula - Parliament of South Africa |url=https://www.parliament.gov.za/person-details/108 |website=parliament.gov.za |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1954|12|07|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Durban]], [[Natal Province]], [[South Africa]]\n| death_date          =  \n| death_place         = \n| citizenship         =\n| nationality         = [[South Africa]]n\n| party               = [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] {{small|(2013\u2013present)}}\n| otherparty          = [[African National Congress]] {{small|(1980\u20132013)}}\n| spouse              = \n| partner             =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = [[Inanda, KwaZulu-Natal]]\n| education           = \n| alma_mater          = [[Durban University of Technology]]\n| occupation          = Member of Parliament\n| profession          = Politician\n| known_for           = Her refusal to speak [[English language|English]] in Parliament\n| committees          = Portfolio Committee on Women, Youth and Persons with Disabilities (Alternate Member)\n| portfolio           = \n| awards              =  \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Makoti Sibongile Khawula''' (born 7 December 1954) is a [[Zulu people|Zulu]] South African politician and previous anti-apartheid activist from [[KwaZulu-Natal]] serving  as a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]] for the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] (EFF) since 2014. Khawula is known for her refusal to speak English in Parliament.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zulu |first1=Makhosandile |title=EFF MP maKhawula calls Mabuza a liar |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/2002728/eff-mp-makhawula-calls-mabuza-a-liar/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=30 August 2018|quote=Khawula is known for speaking IsiZulu in parliament and on social media platforms has gained popularity for providing a degree of entertainment during sessions in the house.}}</ref><ref name=\"news24\" />\n==Early life and education==\nKhawula was born on 7 December 1954 in [[Durban]] in the former [[Natal Province]]. She only fulfilled grade 8 while attending school. She later completed a certficate in surveying from the [[Durban University of Technology]] and a Doctors For Life course in Home Based Care.<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\" />\n==Political career==\n===Political activism===\nKhawula joined the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) and participated in anti-apartheid activities in the Durban communities of [[Inanda, KwaZulu-Natal|Inanda]] and [[KwaMashu]] in the 1980s.<ref name=\"pa\">{{cite web |title=Ms Makoti Sibongile Khawula (EFF) - Interview |url=https://www.pa.org.za/blog/ms-makoti-sibongile-khawula-eff |website=People's Assembly |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> She became an organiser for the ANC in 1990. Within the ANC, she was a member of the party's [[African National Congress Women's League|Women's League]], a provincial election organiser in 1994 and a development activist for the party. She became a member of the party's Regional Executive Committee in 2013. She was also the chairperson of both the [[South African Communist Party]] (SACP) and [[South African National Civic Organisation]] (SANCO) in ward 54 of the [[eThekwini Metropolitan Municipality]].<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\" /> She left the ANC in 2013 and joined the newly-formed EFF in the same year.<ref name=\"pa\" />\n===Parliamentary career===\nKhawula became a Member of Parliament on 21 May 2014 following the [[2014 South African general election|2014 general elections]]. She was assigned to serve on the Portfolio Committee on Water and Sanitation and the Portfolio Committee on Women in the Presidency.<ref name=\"news24\">{{cite news |last1=Evans |first1=Jenni |title=Meet the EFF MP who refuses to speak English in Parliament |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/meet-the-eff-mp-who-refuses-to-speak-english-in-parliament-20151222 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=22 December 2015 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nShe soon became known for her refusal to speak English in Parliament. She speaks either [[Zulu language|isiZulu]] or [[Xhosa language|isiXhosa]] when delivering speeches or asking oratory questions. She insists that she will speak the language of her constituency.<ref name=\"news24\" />\n\nShe was re-elected to a second term in the [[2019 South African general election|2019 general elections]]. She now serves as an Alternate Member of the  Portfolio Committee on Women, Youth, Children and People with Disability.<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nIn the Register of Members' Interests for 2014, Khawula declared that she received social grants for two foster children.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Davis |first1=Rebecca |title=MPs\u2019 financial interests revealed: Some cats are fatter than others |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2014-09-19-mps-financial-interests-revealed-some-cats-are-fatter-than-others/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=19 September 2014}}</ref> These were not part of the 2015 register.<ref name=\"news24\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/makoti-sibongile-khawula/ Ms Makoti Sibongile Khawula \u2013 People's Assembly]\n\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n{{Economic Freedom Fighters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khawula, Makoti}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Economic Freedom Fighters politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Zulu people]]\n[[Category:People from Durban]]\n[[Category:Anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n[[Category:People from KwaZulu-Natal]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Kwa-Zulu Natal]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Makoti Khawula\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Parliament of South Africa|MP]]\n| image               = Makoti Khawula sworn in.png\n| image_size          = \n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Khawula at her swearing-in in May 2019\n| office              = Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]\n| status              = \n| term_start          = 21 May 2014\n| term_end            = \n| constituency        = [[KwaZulu-Natal]]\n| birthname           = Makoti Sibongile Khawula<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\">{{cite web |title=Ms Makoti Sibongile Khawula - Parliament of South Africa |url=https://www.parliament.gov.za/person-details/108 |website=parliament.gov.za |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1954|12|07|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Durban]], [[Natal Province]], [[South Africa]]\n| death_date          =  \n| death_place         = \n| citizenship         =\n| nationality         = [[South Africa]]n\n| party               = [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] {{small|(2013\u2013present)}}\n| otherparty          = [[African National Congress]] {{small|(1980\u20132013)}}\n| spouse              = \n| partner             =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = [[Inanda, KwaZulu-Natal]]\n| education           = \n| alma_mater          = [[Durban University of Technology]]\n| occupation          = Member of Parliament\n| profession          = Politician\n| known_for           = Her refusal to speak [[English language|English]] in Parliament\n| committees          = Portfolio Committee on Women, Youth and Persons with Disabilities (Alternate Member)\n| portfolio           = \n| awards              =  \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Makoti Sibongile Khawula''' (born 7 December 1954) is a [[Zulu people|Zulu]] South African politician and previous anti-apartheid activist from [[KwaZulu-Natal]] serving  as a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]] for the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] (EFF) since 2014. Khawula is known for her refusal to speak English in Parliament.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zulu |first1=Makhosandile |title=EFF MP maKhawula calls Mabuza a liar |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/2002728/eff-mp-makhawula-calls-mabuza-a-liar/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=30 August 2018|quote=Khawula is known for speaking IsiZulu in parliament and on social media platforms has gained popularity for providing a degree of entertainment during sessions in the house.}}</ref><ref name=\"news24\" />\n==Early life and education==\nKhawula was born on 7 December 1954 in [[Durban]] in the former [[Natal Province]]. She only fulfilled grade 8 while attending school. She later completed a certficate in surveying from the [[Durban University of Technology]] and a Doctors For Life course in Home Based Care.<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\" />\n==Political career==\n===Political activism===\nKhawula joined the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) and participated in anti-apartheid activities in the Durban communities of [[Inanda, KwaZulu-Natal|Inanda]] and [[KwaMashu]] in the 1980s.<ref name=\"pa\">{{cite web |title=Ms Makoti Sibongile Khawula (EFF) - Interview |url=https://www.pa.org.za/blog/ms-makoti-sibongile-khawula-eff |website=People's Assembly |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> She became an organiser for the ANC in 1990. Within the ANC, she was a member of the party's [[African National Congress Women's League|Women's League]], a provincial election organiser in 1994 and a development activist for the party. She became a member of the party's Regional Executive Committee in 2013. She was also the chairperson of both the [[South African Communist Party]] (SACP) and [[South African National Civic Organisation]] (SANCO) in ward 54 of the [[eThekwini Metropolitan Municipality]].<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\" /> She left the ANC in 2013 and joined the newly-formed EFF in the same year.<ref name=\"pa\" />\n===Parliamentary career===\nKhawula became a Member of Parliament on 21 May 2014 following the [[2014 South African general election|2014 general elections]]. She was assigned to serve on the Portfolio Committee on Water and Sanitation and the Portfolio Committee on Women in the Presidency.<ref name=\"news24\">{{cite news |last1=Evans |first1=Jenni |title=Meet the EFF MP who refuses to speak English in Parliament |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/meet-the-eff-mp-who-refuses-to-speak-english-in-parliament-20151222 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=22 December 2015 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nShe soon became known for her refusal to speak English in Parliament. She speaks either [[Zulu people|isiZulu]] or [[Xhosa language|isiXhosa]] when delivering speeches or asking oratory questions. She insists that she will speak the language of her constituency.<ref name=\"news24\" />\n\nShe was re-elected to a second term in the [[2019 South African general election|2019 general elections]]. She now serves as an Alternate Member of the  Portfolio Committee on Women, Youth, Children and People with Disability.<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nIn the Register of Members' Interests for 2014, Khawula declared that she received social grants for two foster children.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Davis |first1=Rebecca |title=MPs\u2019 financial interests revealed: Some cats are fatter than others |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2014-09-19-mps-financial-interests-revealed-some-cats-are-fatter-than-others/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=19 September 2014}}</ref> These were not part of the 2015 register.<ref name=\"news24\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/makoti-sibongile-khawula/ Ms Makoti Sibongile Khawula \u2013 People's Assembly]\n\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n{{Economic Freedom Fighters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khawula, Makoti}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Economic Freedom Fighters politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Zulu people]]\n[[Category:People from Durban]]\n[[Category:Anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n[[Category:People from KwaZulu-Natal]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Kwa-Zulu Natal]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Makoti_Khawula"}
{"title_page": "Transylvanian Society of Dracula", "text_new": "{{primary sources|date=September 2008}}\nThe '''Transylvanian Society of Dracula''' ('''TSD''') is a cultural-historic, non-profit, non-governmental organization. Its members include Romanian and international scholars, folklorists, historians, esoterists, writers, cultural anthropologists, and individuals interested in comparative religion, magic and mythology.<ref>[http://www.answers.com/Transylvanian%20Society%20of%20Dracula TSD information on Answers.com]</ref> The TSD organizes scholarly activities both in Romania and abroad,<ref>[http://wiki.benecke.com/index.php?title=Transylvanian_Society_of_Dracula#Photographs_.26_more_from_Congresses Photographs and more from TSD Congresses] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616015535/http://wiki.benecke.com/index.php?title=Transylvanian_Society_of_Dracula#Photographs_.26_more_from_Congresses |date=2008-06-16 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.ucs.mun.ca/~emiller/first_congress.html The first Dracula Congress]</ref> as well as tours to sites of TSD interest in Romania.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/travel/deals/inside/2005-10-26-column_x.htm Information about the tours, USAToday.com]</ref>\nSome high ranked Romanian members make money out of the touristic activities of the organization, through the Company of Mysterious Journeys tourist agency. Modifications to this agency have occurred since the founder Nicolae Paduraru died. The Halloween 2011 tour, for example, did not include [[Bran Castle]] or [[Curtea Veche]] -in spite of what was published in their web site-, but it included a beauty pageant. One of the Romanian members of TSD working at the agency was one of the presenters of such pageant.\n\n== History ==\nTSD was founded in the early 1990s by a group of writers, Romanian scholars, tourism experts, and others interested in [[Dracula]] and vampire folklore in [[Romania]]. Taking the lead was Nicolae Paduraru, formerly with the Romanian Ministry of Tourism. Paduraru died in May 2009<ref>[http://www.cesnur.org/2009/paduraru.htm Nicolae Paduraru (1937-2009), founder of the Transylvanian Society of Dracula: An Obituary]</ref>\n\nIn May 1995, the TSD chapter in Romania organized the first World Dracula Congress. This event attracted scholars and aficionados from many countries.  The list of speakers included some of the world's leading experts in the field, like [[Gordon Melton]], [[Elizabeth Miller (academic)|Elizabeth Miller]], Matei Cazacu and Clive Letherdale. The congress marked the first time when Romanian folklorists have the opportunity to share their knowledge and research in both the vampire legend and the history of Vlad Tepes with their counterparts in the West.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=brj7yfaBkPAC ''Bram Stoker's Dracula''] By Carol Margaret Davison, Paul Simpson-Housley</ref>\n\nDuring the conference both the American and the Canadian chapter were established by [[J. Gordon Melton]] and Elizabeth Miller<ref>[http://www.ucs.mun.ca/~emiller/elizabeth_miller.html Prof. Elizabeth Miller] homepage</ref> respectively. The North American chapter is housed at Pennsylvania's Kutztown University who publishes ''The Journal of Dracula Studies'' each year. Edited by Dr Anne DeLong and Dr. Curt Herr, the peer-reviewed journal publishes essays on Vampire Studies from around the world. A short time later, an Italian chapter was founded by [[Massimo Introvigne]], and since 2001, there is a German chapter<ref>[http://wiki.benecke.com/index.php?title=Transylvanian_Society_of_Dracula TSD Consul in the Rhine Parts (TSD Konsul der Rheinlande)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616015535/http://wiki.benecke.com/index.php?title=Transylvanian_Society_of_Dracula |date=2008-06-16 }}</ref> run by Dr. [[Mark Benecke]]. In 2006 a Russian Chapter was opened. It is run by Mrs. Ekaterina Buley.\n\n== TSD in North America ==\nThe Canadian Chapter of the Transylvanian Society of Dracula was formed in 1995 following the first World Dracula Congress in Romania, as non-profit corporation.  The North American chapter publishes the MLA indexed ''[https://www.kutztown.edu/academics/colleges-and-departments/liberal-arts-and-sciences/departments/english/journal-of-dracula-studies.html Journal of Dracula Studies]''is published by the Kutztown University\u2019s English department. The North American Chapter of the Transylvanian Society of Dracula (TSD) was formed at Kutztown University in Pennsylvania in 2016<ref>https://kutztownenglish.com/transylvania-society-of-dracula/</ref>.\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ucs.mun.ca/~emiller/ Canadian Chapter] - Elizabeth Miller\n* [http://www.transilvania71.narod.ru/ The Russian Chapter] - Ekaterina Buley\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080616015535/http://wiki.benecke.com/index.php?title=Transylvanian_Society_of_Dracula The German Chapter] - Mark Benecke (dead link)\n* [http://www.cesnur.org/Dracula.htm The Italian Chapter]\n* [http://www.cesnur.org/2008/tsd_02.htm One of the TSD] 2008 symposium programme\n* [http://www.mysterious-journeys.com/dracula_tours/latest_news/ The official news bulletin]\n* [http://www.nationalgeographic.nl/magazine/archief.php?idm=494&idmagm=77&action=bekijkartikel TSD referred to in the Dutch version of ''National Geographic Magazine'']{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}, March 2006 \n* [https://www.flickr.com/groups/transylvaniansocietyofdracula/ TSD's flickr] page\n\n{{Dracula}}\n\n[[Category:Dracula]]\n[[Category:Cultural organizations based in Romania]]\n[[Category:Transylvania]]\n[[Category:Vampirism]]\n[[Category:History organizations based in Romania]]\n", "text_old": "{{primary sources|date=September 2008}}\nThe '''Transylvanian Society of Dracula''' ('''TSD''') is a cultural-historic, non-profit, non-governmental organization. Its members include Romanian and international scholars, folklorists, historians, esoterists, writers, cultural anthropologists, and individuals interested in comparative religion, magic and mythology.<ref>[http://www.answers.com/Transylvanian%20Society%20of%20Dracula TSD information on Answers.com]</ref> The TSD organizes scholarly activities both in Romania and abroad,<ref>[http://wiki.benecke.com/index.php?title=Transylvanian_Society_of_Dracula#Photographs_.26_more_from_Congresses Photographs and more from TSD Congresses] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616015535/http://wiki.benecke.com/index.php?title=Transylvanian_Society_of_Dracula#Photographs_.26_more_from_Congresses |date=2008-06-16 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.ucs.mun.ca/~emiller/first_congress.html The first Dracula Congress]</ref> as well as tours to sites of TSD interest in Romania.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/travel/deals/inside/2005-10-26-column_x.htm Information about the tours, USAToday.com]</ref>\nSome high ranked Romanian members make money out of the touristic activities of the organization, through the Company of Mysterious Journeys tourist agency. Modifications to this agency have occurred since the founder Nicolae Paduraru died. The Halloween 2011 tour, for example, did not include [[Bran Castle]] or [[Curtea Veche]] -in spite of what was published in their web site-, but it included a beauty pageant. One of the Romanian members of TSD working at the agency was one of the presenters of such pageant.\n\n== History ==\nTSD was founded in the early 1990s by a group of writers, Romanian scholars, tourism experts, and others interested in [[Dracula]] and vampire folklore in [[Romania]]. Taking the lead was Nicolae Paduraru, formerly with the Romanian Ministry of Tourism. Paduraru died in May 2009<ref>[http://www.cesnur.org/2009/paduraru.htm Nicolae Paduraru (1937-2009), founder of the Transylvanian Society of Dracula: An Obituary]</ref>\n\nIn May 1995, the TSD chapter in Romania organized the first World Dracula Congress. This event attracted scholars and aficionados from many countries.  The list of speakers included some of the world's leading experts in the field, like [[Gordon Melton]], [[Elizabeth Miller (academic)|Elizabeth Miller]], Matei Cazacu and Clive Letherdale. The congress marked the first time when Romanian folklorists have the opportunity to share their knowledge and research in both the vampire legend and the history of Vlad Tepes with their counterparts in the West.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=brj7yfaBkPAC ''Bram Stoker's Dracula''] By Carol Margaret Davison, Paul Simpson-Housley</ref>\n\nDuring the conference both the American and the Canadian chapter were established by [[J. Gordon Melton]] and Elizabeth Miller<ref>[http://www.ucs.mun.ca/~emiller/elizabeth_miller.html Prof. Elizabeth Miller] homepage</ref> respectively. The North American chapter is housed at Pennsylvania's Kutztown University who publishes ''The Journal of Dracula Studies'' each year. Edited by Dr Anne DeLong and Dr. Curt Herr, the peer-reviewed journal publishes essays on Vampire Studies from around the world. A short time later, an Italian chapter was founded by [[Massimo Introvigne]], and since 2001, there is a German chapter<ref>[http://wiki.benecke.com/index.php?title=Transylvanian_Society_of_Dracula TSD Consul in the Rhine Parts (TSD Konsul der Rheinlande)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616015535/http://wiki.benecke.com/index.php?title=Transylvanian_Society_of_Dracula |date=2008-06-16 }}</ref> run by Dr. [[Mark Benecke]]. In 2006 a Russian Chapter was opened. It is run by Mrs. Ekaterina Buley.\n\n== TSD in North America ==\nThe Canadian Chapter of the Transylvanian Society of Dracula was formed in 1995 following the first World Dracula Congress in Romania, as non-profit corporation.  The North American chapter publishes the MLA indexed ''[https://kutztownenglish.com/2015/04/09/journal-of-dracula-studies/ Journal of Dracula Studies]''is published by the Kutztown University\u2019s English department. The North American Chapter of the Transylvanian Society of Dracula (TSD) was formed at Kutztown University in Pennsylvania in 2016<ref>https://kutztownenglish.com/transylvania-society-of-dracula/</ref>.\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ucs.mun.ca/~emiller/ Canadian Chapter] - Elizabeth Miller\n* [http://www.transilvania71.narod.ru/ The Russian Chapter] - Ekaterina Buley\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080616015535/http://wiki.benecke.com/index.php?title=Transylvanian_Society_of_Dracula The German Chapter] - Mark Benecke (dead link)\n* [http://www.cesnur.org/Dracula.htm The Italian Chapter]\n* [http://www.cesnur.org/2008/tsd_02.htm One of the TSD] 2008 symposium programme\n* [http://www.mysterious-journeys.com/dracula_tours/latest_news/ The official news bulletin]\n* [http://www.nationalgeographic.nl/magazine/archief.php?idm=494&idmagm=77&action=bekijkartikel TSD referred to in the Dutch version of ''National Geographic Magazine'']{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}, March 2006 \n* [https://www.flickr.com/groups/transylvaniansocietyofdracula/ TSD's flickr] page\n\n{{Dracula}}\n\n[[Category:Dracula]]\n[[Category:Cultural organizations based in Romania]]\n[[Category:Transylvania]]\n[[Category:Vampirism]]\n[[Category:History organizations based in Romania]]\n", "name_user": "Jasonnolan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTSD in North America:fixed bad URL to JDS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transylvanian_Society_of_Dracula"}
{"title_page": "Drifting (motorsport)", "text_new": "[[File:Comparison between two drifting techniques.svg|thumb|A diagram showing two different drifting techniques]]\n'''Drifting''' is a [[driving]] technique where the driver intentionally [[Understeer and oversteer|oversteers]], with loss of traction, while maintaining control and driving the car through the entirety of a corner. The technique causes the rear [[slip angle]] to exceed the front slip angle to such an extent that often the front wheels are pointing in the opposite direction to the turn (e.g. car is turning left, wheels are pointed right or vice versa, also known as [[opposite lock]] or [[Countersteering#Other uses|counter-steering]]).  The sport of drifting is not to be confused with the ''four wheel drift'', a classic cornering technique established in [[Grand Prix motor racing|Grand Prix]] and sports car racing. Drifting is traditionally done by [[clutch]] kicking, then intentionally oversteering and countersteering.\n\nAs a [[Motorsport|motoring]] discipline, drifting competitions were first popularized in Japan in the 1970s and further popularized by the 1995 manga series ''[[Initial D]]''. Drifting competitions are held worldwide and are judged according to the speed, angle, showmanship and line taken through a corner or set of corners.<ref>{{cite book|last=Abdulrahim |first=M. |title=SAE Technical Paper Series |id=ITSD |chapter=On the Dynamics of Automobile Drifting |volume=1 |publisher=University of Florida |year=2006 |doi=10.4271/2006-01-1019 |citeseerx=10.1.1.103.9227 }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Origin ===\nJapan was the birthplace of drifting.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McKirdy |first1=Andrew |title=Drifting: Japan-born street sport roars onto global stage |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2017/10/04/more-sports/auto-racing/drifting-japan-born-street-sport-roars-onto-global-stage/#.W07Z9tIzaUm |website=The Japan Times |accessdate=18 July 2018 |date=October 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Banner |first1=Justin |title=The History of Drifting and The Future of Formula Drift |url=https://motoiq.com/The-History-of-Drifting-and-The-Future-of-Formula-Drift/ |website=MotoIQ |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Legendary Toyota AE86 and the Origins of Drift Racing |url=https://injapan.gaijinpot.com/uncategorized/2013/07/02/origins-of-drift-racing-legendary-toyota-ae86/ |website=GaijinPot |accessdate=18 July 2018 |date=July 2, 2013}}</ref> It was most popular in the [[Japanese Touring Car Championship|All Japan Touring Car Championship]] races. Famous [[Motorcycle sport|motorcyclist]] turned driver [[Kunimitsu Takahashi]] was the foremost creator of drifting techniques in the 1970s. This earned him several championships and a legion of fans who enjoyed the spectacle of smoking tires. The [[bias-ply]] racing tires of the 1960s&ndash;1980s lent themselves to driving styles with a high slip angle. As professional racers in Japan drove this way, so did street racers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dixon |first1=Chris |title=DRIVING; Drifting: The Fast Art of the Controlled Slide |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/05/07/travel/driving-drifting-the-fast-art-of-the-controlled-slide.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=18 July 2018 |date=May 7, 2004}}</ref>\n\n[[Keiichi Tsuchiya]], known as the {{Nihongo|\"Drift King\"|\u30c9\u30ea\u30d5\u30c8\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\n|Dorifuto Kingu}}, became particularly interested by Takahashi's drift techniques. Tsuchiya began practicing his drifting skills on the [[T\u014dge|mountain roads]] of Japan, and quickly gained a reputation amongst the racing crowd. In 1987, several popular car magazines and tuning garages agreed to produce a video of Tsuchiya's drifting skills. The video, known as ''Pluspy'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OVyxHVhNNgY|title=Keiichi Tsuchiya - Pluspy (part 1)|last=lnsania|date=6 August 2007|publisher=|access-date=29 March 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> became a hit and inspired many of the professional drifting drivers on the circuits today. In 1988, alongside [[Option (car magazine)|''Option'' magazine]] founder and [[Editing|chief editor]] Daijiro Inada, he helped to organize one of the first events specifically for drifting called the D1 Grand Prix. He has also drifted through every turn in [[Tsukuba Circuit]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n=== Popularity ===\nOne of the earliest recorded drift events outside Japan took place in 1996 at [[Willow Springs Raceway]] in [[Willow Springs, Kern County, California|Willow Springs]], [[California]], hosted by the Japanese drifting magazine and organization [[Option (car magazine)|''Option'']]. Daijiro Inada (founder of the Japanese D1 Grand Prix), the [[National Hot Rod Association|NHRA]] [[Funny Car]] [[Drag racing|drag racer]] Kenji Okazaki, and Keiichi Tsuchiya gave demonstrations in a [[Nissan 180SX]] that the magazine had brought over from Japan. Entrants included [[Rhys Millen]] and Bryan Norris.<ref>''Super Street'', Issue 4, December 1996</ref> Drifting has since exploded into a form of motorsport in North America, Australia, Asia and Europe.\n\nDrifting has evolved into a competitive sport where drivers compete (almost exclusively in rear-wheel-drive cars) to earn points from judges based on various factors. At the top levels of competition, the [[D1 Grand Prix]] in Japan pioneered the sport. Other events such as Drift Games Extreme (formally known as the IDC \u2014 Irish Drift Championship) in [[Ireland]], [[Formula D]] in the [[United States]], [[Drift Allstars]], King of Europe, Drift Masters and the [[British Drift Championship]] in Europe, [[World Drift Series|WDS]] in China, [[Russian Drift Series|RDS]] in Russia, [[Formula Drift Asia]] in the Malaysia/Singapore/Thailand/Indonesia, [[NZ Drift Series]] in New Zealand, the Australian Drifting Grand Prix, and the Greek Drift Championship (Drift Wars) have come along to further expand it into a legitimate motorsport worldwide. Drivers within these series are able to keep their cars sliding for extended periods of time, often linking several turns.\n\n== Drift competition ==\nDrifting competitions are judged based on line, angle, speed, style and show factor. Line involves taking the correct line, which is usually announced beforehand by judges. The show factor is based on many things, such as the amount of smoke, how close the car is to the wall or designated clipping point, giving the crowd's reaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YCcuUADvAfE |title=How drifting is judged |publisher=Youtube.com |date=|accessdate=2011-08-08}}</ref> The desired line is usually dictated by the judge or judges, who describe their desired line as well as highlight areas of importance, such as clipping zones, clipping points and touch-and-go areas.\n\n* Angle is the angle of a car and, more importantly, the turned wheels in a drift, speed is the speed entering a turn, the speed through a turn, and the speed exiting the turn; faster is better. Style is scored on a combination of a rate-to-angle during the initiation, how fluid the car looks through the course, and how committed the driver is through the course.\n* The rate-to-angle is how quickly during {{Nihongo|initiation|\u632f\u51fa\u3057|furidashi}} or {{Nihongo|transitions|\u632f\u66ff\u3057|furikaeshi}} a car gets to its sliding angle.\n* Fluidity is how smoothly a driver maneuvers their car around the course, taking into account the amount of correction that a driver applies through turns, and the smoothness with which the car transitions from one corner to the next.\n* Commitment is about how much throttle the driver applies, and the confidence and dedication the driver shows when approaching track edges and barriers. The higher the rate-to-angle, the more speed and angle a driver can carry through the course. In addition, the fewer corrections they apply through the course and the closer they drive to the track edges or barriers, the higher their style score.\n\n[[File:Team Drift.jpg|thumb|Team Drift Competition in [[Melbourne]]]]\nJudging takes place on just a small part of the circuit, a few linking corners that provide good viewing, and opportunities for drifting. The rest of the circuit is irrelevant, but it pertains to controlling the temperature of the tires and setting the car up for the first judged corner. In [[tandem]] passes, the lead driver (in the lead car, Senko) often feints their entry to the first corner to upset the chase driver (in the chase car, Atooi); however, in some European series, this practice is frowned upon by judges and considered foul play, resulting in deduction of points.\n\nThere are typically two sessions &ndash; a qualifying or practice session, and a final session. In qualifying sessions, referred to as {{Nihongo|\"solo runs\"|\u5358\u8d70|tans\u014d}}, drifters get individual passes in front of judges (who may or may not be the final judges) to try to make the final 16. This is often on the day preceding the final.\n\nThe finals are tandem passes called {{Nihongo|\"chases\"|\u8ffd\u8d70|tsuis\u014d}}. Drivers are paired off, and each heat comprises two passes, with each driver taking a turn to lead. The best of the eight heats go to the next four, to the next two, to the final. The passes are judged as explained above; however, there are some provisos such as:\n\n* Overtaking the lead car under drift conditions is allowed if the chasing car doesn't interrupt the lead car's drift.\n* Overtaking the lead car under grip conditions automatically forfeits a pass.\n* Spinning forfeits a pass, unless the other driver also spins.\n* Increasing the lead under drift conditions helps to win a pass.\n* Maintaining a close gap while chasing under drift conditions helps to win a pass.\n*The level of smoke from the tires is also a factor.\n\nPoints are awarded for each pass, and usually, one driver prevails. Sometimes, the judges cannot agree, or cannot decide, or a crowd vocally disagrees with the judge's decision.<ref>{{cite web|title=One More Time (OMT)|url=http://formulad.com/info/judging-info.php|website=Formula D|accessdate=15 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625122256/http://formulad.com/info/judging-info.php|archive-date=25 June 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In such cases, more passes may be run until a winner is produced. On occasion, mechanical failure determines the battle's outcome, either during or preceding a heat. If a car cannot enter a tandem battle, the remaining entrant (who automatically advances) will give a solo demonstration pass. In the event of apparently close or tied runs, crowds often demonstrate their desire for another run with chants of 'one more time'.<ref>[http://www.turbomagazine.com/features/0401tur_drifting_inaugural_d1_grand_prix/index.html Drift Mania! Inaugural D1 Grand Prix presented by Yokohama August 31, 2003], Turbo Magazine. Retrieved August 25, 2007.</ref>\n\n=== Outside of Japan ===\nThere is some regional variation. For example, in Australia, the chase car is judged on how accurately it emulates the drift of the lead car, as opposed to being judged on its own merit \u2014 this is only taken into consideration by the judges if the lead car is on the appropriate racing line.<ref>{{cite web|title=Australian Drifting Grand Prix sporting regulations, section 2.10.1 Judging Criteria - Drift Battles|url=http://australiandriftinggp.com.au/adgp101/sporting-regulations/#judgingcriteriadriftbattles|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316192732/http://australiandriftinggp.com.au/adgp101/sporting-regulations/|archivedate=16 March 2017}}</ref> Other variations of the tans\u014d/tsuis\u014d and the tans\u014d-only method is multi-car group judging, seen in [[Drift Tengoku]] videos where the four-car team is judged in groups.<ref>{{cite web|title=Australian Judging|url=http://trackbattle.com.au/adgp/events/judging/|website=Track Battle|accessdate=15 July 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715202037/http://trackbattle.com.au/adgp/events/judging/|archivedate=15 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe D1GP drift series has been prototyping and fine-tuning an electronic judging system based on custom sensors that record and transmit car data to a computer that judges the run. This system is also being tested in some European series. It is designed to remove subjectivity and/or predisposition of judges. Usually the track for such a system is broken up into several sections (usually three) and the system automatically generates scores based on speed, angle and fluidity of the driver in each section, combining the scores for the final score. In certain situations judges can change or overrule a score, which happens, though rarely.\n\nFormula Drift is the top United States Drifting series. Its judging style for competition is based on line, angle, and speed. When judging for line the driver is judged based on their ability to stay on the line set in place by the judges. Points are allocated to outside zones and inner clips, and are also allocated to touch and go areas. Angle is the drivers ability to maintain a high level of angle that will be set by the angle judge in the drivers meeting. Style is judges based on three areas of focus; initiation, fluidity, and commitment. Initiation is based on how early and smooth the driver initiates into a drift. Fluidity is how smooth the driver drives from lock to lock, high angles of drift, and just overall smoothness on the track. Commitment is judges on consistent throttle throughout, and how close the driver is willing to get to walls and clipping points.<ref>http://static.formulad.com/docs/2017/2017%20Formula%20Drift%20Pro%20Sporting%20Regulations%20Version%201.0.pdf</ref>\n\nThe King of Europe Drift ProSeries has developed its own [[telemetry]] system, which uses GPS data to accurately measure speed, angle and line, thus leading to a very objective result for the qualifying sessions.<ref>Jefferies, Bill (July 11, 2014). [http://www.wanganwarriors.com/king-of-europe-battle-for-the-throne/ \"KING OF EUROPE: BATTLE FOR THE THRONE\"]. Wangan Warriors. Retrieved July 26, 2019.</ref>\n\n== Drift cars ==\n[[File:King of Europe Round 3 Lydden Hill 2014 (14356011899).jpg|thumb|Steve Moore drifting his [[Nissan Silvia]] (S14) around Lydden Hill at King of Europe Round 3 (2014)]]\n\nDrift cars are usually light- to moderate-weight rear-wheel-drive coupes and sedans, offering a large range of power levels. There have also been [[all-wheel drive]] cars that have been converted to rear-wheel drive such as the [[Subaru Impreza|Subaru WRX]], [[Toyota Avensis]], [[Scion tC]], [[Mitsubishi Lancer Evolution]] and [[Nissan GT-R]]. Early on, AWD cars without conversion were allowed in some drifting competitions, and usually the rules allowed only a certain percentage of power to be sent to the front wheels, but they are banned in most (if not all) drifting competitions today.\n\nDespite the possibility of obtaining desirable [[Japanese domestic market]] vehicles in continents outside Japan,<ref>Savage, J. (2010), \"Tuner Cars\", Edge Books</ref> drifters in other countries prefer to use local versions of the same cars (for example, a [[Nissan 240SX]] instead of a [[Nissan Silvia|Nissan Silvia S13]], etc.), or even [[Domestic market|domestic cars]]. A high volume of Japanese imports were brought to countries such as Australia and New Zealand, however it is not unusual to see Australian/New Zealand domestic vehicles such as the [[Holden]] [[Holden Commodore|Commodore]] or [[Ford Motor Company of Australia|Ford]] [[Ford Falcon (Australia)|Falcon]] used in drifting competitions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zercustoms.com/news/Ford-Typhoon-Drifting-Car-2.php |title=Ford Typhoon Drifting Car - Page 2 |publisher=[[ZerCustoms]] |date=2006-09-19 |access-date=8 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111010113712/http://www.zercustoms.com/news/Ford-Typhoon-Drifting-Car-2.php |archive-date=10 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe American market saw a relatively high volume of JDM cars being imported over the last decade, despite Japanese domestic vehicles being right-hand-drive only.<ref>Alvendia, A. (2006), \"Drifting Sideways: From Japan To America\", Motorbooks</ref> Locally-sold imports such as the [[Lexus SC]] and Nissan 240SX feature heavily in American drifting, but they are usually modified with JDM engines to mirror their Japanese domestic equivalents (usually with a [[Toyota JZ engine|Toyota JZ-GTE]] or Nissan CA18DET/SR20DET/RB26DETT respectively).<ref>Schuette, S \u201cDrift Cars\u201d, Capstone Press, 2007</ref>\n\nIn the UK, there are a high level of Japanese imports used within the drifting scene, due in part to the UK sharing a right-hand drive layout with Japan. However, these cars often cost more than UK-market cars, partly due to import costs. There are plenty of UK and European models used as drift cars as well \u2014 older BMWs are particularly prominent due to cost and availability, with Volvo 300 series and Ford Sierras also proving popular.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.driftworks.com/drifting/|title=What is Drifting?|author=|date=|work=DriftWorks.com|access-date=29 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trampdrift.eu/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=51&Itemid=60|title=Article on Trampdrift - What to buy|author=|date=|work=Trampdrift.eu|access-date=29 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the Formula Drift Professional series, cars range from highly tuned Japanese automobiles reflecting the original styles of drifting to all-new age makes and models. Due to no power limit restrictions in the series, it is not uncommon for competitors to use a variety of different powerplants. Popular variations of Chevrolet [[LS based GM small-block engine|LS engines]] are often seen bolted down to Japanese frames.<ref>Chen, L \u201cHorsepower Wars\u201d, Speed Hunters, 2015</ref>\n\nIn the King of Europe Drift Series, the main professional drift series in Europe, BMW models have long ruled the scene, winning event after event, year after year. The most successful models include the [[E30 M3|E30]], [[E36 M3|E36]] and [[E46 M3|E46]], which also present an advantage in cost (being more affordable than their Japanese rivals). For a few years, BMW V8 engine swaps were the most popular, providing a healthy 300 to 400 horsepower output. With the continuous evolution of the sport, however, these have now become obsolete, making way for more powerful American V8 engines or classic Toyota 2JZ-GTE engines.\n\nAs an example, the top 15 cars in the 2003 D1GP,<ref name=\"db1\">{{cite book|title=Drift Battle 1|last=Ellis|first=Ben|publisher=Express Motoring Publications|year=2004|page=24|display-authors=etal}}</ref> top 10 in the 2004 D1GP,<ref name=\"db4\">{{cite book|title=Drift Battle 4|last=Ellis|first=Ben|publisher=Express Motoring Publications|year=2004|page=22|display-authors=etal}}</ref> and top 10 in the 2005 D1GP<ref name=\"db12\">{{cite book|title=Drift Battle 12|last=Ellis|first=Ben|publisher=Express Motoring Publications|year=2005|page=77|display-authors=etal}}\n</ref> were as follows:\n\n[[File:D1NZ07072007.jpg|thumb|Nissan Silvia S15 drifting]]\n<!--Do not edit the information in the table below. It is derived from the printed sources listed above. Add new/additional information elsewhere.-->\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Car !! Model !! 2003 !! 2004 !! 2005\n|-\n| [[Nissan Silvia]] || S15 || 6 cars || 5 cars || 3 cars\n|-\n| [[Toyota AE86|Toyota Levin/Trueno]] || AE86 || 3 cars || 3 cars || 2 cars\n|-\n| [[Mazda RX-7]] || FD3S || 2 cars || 1 car || 2 cars\n|-\n| [[Nissan Skyline]] || R34 || 1 car || 1 car || 1 car\n|-\n| Nissan Silvia || S13 || 5 cars ||   ||\n|-\n| [[Toyota Chaser]] || JZX100 || 1 car ||   ||\n|-\n| [[Subaru Impreza]] || GD (RWD) ||   ||   || 1 car\n|-\n| [[Toyota Altezza]] || SXE10 ||   ||   || 1 car\n|}\n\nThe top cars in the Red Bull Drifting Championship were as follows:<ref>[[Red Bull Drifting World Championship]] (2008)</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Driver !! Make !! Model\n|-\n|[[Tanner Foust]] || [[Nissan]] || [[Nissan 350Z|350Z]]\n|-\n|[[Ken Gushi]] || [[Scion (automobile)|Scion]] || [[Scion tC|tC]]\n|- \n|[[Kevin Huynh]] || [[Dodge]] || [[Dodge Viper|Viper]]\n|-\n|[[Rhys Millen]] || [[Pontiac]] || [[Pontiac Solstice|Solstice GXP]]\n|-\n|[[Samuel H\u00fcbinette]] || [[Dodge]] || [[Dodge Charger (LX)|Charger]]\n|-\n|[[Chris Forsberg]] || [[Nissan]] || [[Nissan 370Z|370Z]]\n|-\n|}\n\nAs for 2017, the top cars participating in [[Formula Drift]] are the [[Nissan]] [[Nissan 370Z|370Z]], Nissan [[Nissan Silvia|Silvia]] S14, Nissan Silvia S15, [[Toyota]] [[Toyota 86|86]], [[BMW]] E46, [[Ford]] Mustang, and the [[Mazda]] [[Mazda MX-5|MX-5.]]\n\n== Drift tuning ==\n\n=== Drivetrain ===\nA mechanical [[limited slip differential]] (LSD) is considered essential for drifting. Drifting with an open or viscous differential in a sustained slide generally yields relatively less impressive results. All other modifications are secondary to the LSD.<ref name=\"topsecret\">{{cite book | first = Ben | last = Ellis | year = 2004 | pages = 53\u201356 | title = Drift Battle 1 | publisher = Express Motoring Publications | quote = It might surprise some people to see this listed first, but a proper mechanical limited-slip diff is absolutely essential for drift.|display-authors=etal}}\n</ref>\n\nThe preferred form of LSD for drifting is the clutch type, in \"two-way\" form, for its consistent and aggressive lockup behavior under both acceleration and deceleration. Some drift cars use a spool \"differential\", which actually has no differential action at all \u2014 the wheels are locked to each other. Drifters on a budget may use a [[welding|welded]] differential, where the [[differential (mechanics)|side gears]] are welded to give the same effect as a spool. This makes it easier to break rear traction, because it reduces maximum traction in all situations except traveling in a straight line. Welded differentials have an inherent risk involved: due to the tremendous amount of internal stress, the welds may fail and the differential completely lock up leaving the rear wheels immobilized. Helical torque-sensing differentials such as the [[Torsen]] or [[Quaife]] (available on cars in certain stock trims such as the [[Nissan Silvia|S15]], [[Mazda RX-7|FD3S]], [[Mazda MX-5|MX-5]], [[Toyota Supra|JZA80]], and [[Toyota Soarer|UZZ3x]]) are also adequate. It is common for drifters to change the final gear ratio depending on the type of track layout.\n\nThe [[clutch]]es on drift cars tend to be very tough ceramic-brass button or multiple-plate varieties for durability, as well as to allow rapid \"clutch kick\" techniques to upset the grip of the rear wheels. Gearbox and engine mounts are often replaced with [[polyurethane|urethane]] or aluminum mounts, and dampers are added to control the violent motion of the engine and gearbox under these conditions. The driveshafts are often replaced with carbon fiber drive shafts, as they offer the highest rotational mass savings, are stronger than alternative metals, and flexible enough to absorb and dissipate vibrations, thus easing the load on the gearbox as well as the rest of the drivetrain.\n\nGear sets may be replaced with [[Close-ratio transmission|closer ratios]] to keep the engine in the [[power band]], or, on some cars that produce enough power and torque to four-gear transmissions similar to the ones used in NASCAR (such as the Andrews four-speed dog box that [[Vaughn Gittin |Vaughn Gittin Jr.]] ran in his 2016 Mustang<ref>[https://media.ford.com/content/dam/fordmedia/North%20America/US/Events/15%20SEMA/mustang_sema_sheet_09.pdf mustang_sema_sheet_09.pdf]</ref>) with more open-ratio gears, this limits the number of shifts the driver has to do during their run. These may be coarser dog engagement [[Spur gears|straight cut]] gears instead of [[Syncromesh|synchronised]] [[gear#Helical gears|helical gears]], for durability and faster shifting at the expense of noise and refinement. Wealthier drifters may use [[Sequential manual gearbox|sequential gearboxes]] to make gear selection easier and faster, while sequential shift lever adapters can be used to make shifts easier without increasing shift time.\n\n=== Steering and suspension ===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2017}}Steering angles are also crucial as the driver progresses. The first stage of these modifications is usually a modified steering knuckle or upright. Extended control arms can be employed on [[MacPherson strut]] vehicles like the Nissan S-Chassis to allow for more clearance for higher steering angles. Many aftermarket companies have developed full lock kits including modification of the vehicle's original [[scrub radius]], [[Kingpin (automotive part)|kingpin]] axis, [[Ackermann steering geometry|Ackermann angle]], amount of [[bump steer]], [[caster angle]], and kinematics as to maximize front grip and eliminate mechanical bind at steering angles in excess of 60\u00b0. While MacPherson strut vehicles are prevalent in professional drifting, [[double wishbone suspension]] vehicles can also be competitive, with often better caster and camber curves.\n\nSprings and [[shock absorber]]s are also tuned for higher skill levels, depending on track layout.\n\nTypically, dedicated drifting cars are modified to eliminate [[Ackermann steering geometry]], which is included on almost all production cars. While Ackermann geometry is helpful in making a car turn easier, it inhibits the ability to slide sideways at full lock necessary to compete in drifting.\n\n=== Cockpit ===\n[[File:Drift Carnage.jpg|thumb|right|Cleaning up severed bumpers during drift meet]]\nBecause of the high [[centrifugal force]]s encountered during drifting, drivers are usually retained by a [[bucket seat|racing seat]] and [[five-point harness]]. This allows the hands to merely turn the wheel, instead of bracing the body in the seat. The same applies for the feet, which are free to move rapidly between [[Automobile pedal|clutch, brake and accelerator pedals]]. The [[steering wheel]] is usually relatively small, dished, and perfectly round, so that it can be released and allowed to spin in the driver's hands as the caster returns the front wheels to center. The locking knob on the [[hand brake]] is usually replaced with a spin turn knob; this stops the hand brake locking on when pulled. Nearly all drivers move the hand brake location or add an extra hydraulic hand brake actuator for greater braking force. Additional gauges are used to monitor [[Boost gauge|boost levels]], [[oil pressure]] and temperature, intake and [[Engine coolant temperature sensor|coolant temperatures]], and [[Air\u2013fuel ratio|air-fuel ratio]], among other data. Some drivers, especially in larger cars, move the seating position for a better weight distribution, such as [[Daigo Saito]] and his 2014 JZX100 Mk.II Chaser.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://noriyaro.com/2014/10/speed-holes-and-methanol-daigo-saitos-2014-jzx100/|title=SPEED HOLES AND METHANOL: Daigo Saito's 2014 JZX100 : NORIYARO|author=|date=|work=noriyaro.com|accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Tires ===\n[[File:Drift s13 wheel.jpg|thumb|upright|S13 Silvia - tire stretched over a wide rim, increasing sidewall rigidity. The rim has a low offset to increase track.]]\nIn the United States, competitive drifters are required to run US [[Department of transportation|DOT]]-approved (road-legal) tires similar to [[racing slick]]s in rubber composition, but with shallow treads included. This is permitted, with the exception of some major championships including D1GP and Formula Drift, which only permit commercially available tires that are approved by the sanctioning body. Professional drifting has come to the point where grip is tuned into cars to be defeated. It makes for a faster drift necessary in the current professional climate. Tires typically used by drifters are around the DOT tread wear rating of 200. Examples include the Hankook Ventus RS-3, Falken Azenis RT615K, Nitto NT05, Yokohama ADVAN Neova AD08R, and Achilles Radial 123s. Some other companies from Asia have also started developing their technology through sponsoring professional drivers. These companies include Nankang,<ref>[http://www.wreckedmagazine.com/blog/2014/12/08/nankang-tire-set-for-2015-formula-drift-arrival-rumormill/]</ref> Westlake<ref>[http://www.drifting.cz/calendar/race?slug=rd6-westlake-drift-challenge-sosnova]</ref> and Zestino.<ref>[http://www.thebritishdriftchampionship.co.uk/2017/02/28/zestino-tires-uk-partner-british-drift-championship/]</ref> Tires are often modified with [[Tire lettering|lettering]] to give them a more customized look.\n\n== R/C drifting ==\n{{Main|Radio-controlled drifting}}\nR/C drifting refers to the act of drifting with a [[radio-controlled car]]. R/C cars are equipped with special low-grip tires, usually made from [[PVC]] or ABS piping. Some manufacturers make radial drift tires that are made of actual rubber compounds. The car's setup is usually changed to allow it to drift more easily. R/C drifting is most successful on AWD R/C cars. Companies such as Overdose, [[Yokomo]], MST, [[Tamiya Corporation|Tamiya]], [[Team Associated]], and Hobby Products International<ref>[http://www.hpieurope.com/tv13/?channel=9&src=wikipedia HPI R/C Drift Videos] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726073449/http://www.hpieurope.com/tv13/?channel=9&src=wikipedia |date=July 26, 2011 }} and [http://www.hpieurope.com/walk.php?lang=en&id=19 Guide to R/C drifting] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726073454/http://www.hpieurope.com/walk.php?lang=en&id=19 |date=July 26, 2011 }}</ref> have made dedicated drift cars and supported the hobby.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tamiya.com/english/products/58386silvia_tt01d/index.htm |title=1/10 R/C Nismo Coppermix Silvia \uff08TT-01D\uff09 Drift Spec |publisher=Tamiya.com |date=2007-03-08 |accessdate=2011-08-08}}</ref>\n\n== In the media ==\n\n=== Film and television ===\nOne of the key sources responsible for the international spread of drifting is the Japanese manga and anime series ''[[Initial D]]'', which features [[List of Initial D characters#Takumi Fujiwara|Takumi Fujiwara]], a high school student who learns to drift on the Mt. Akina [[t\u014dge]] (mountain pass) using a custom [[Toyota AE86]]. The series features a large number of Japanese performance vehicles, including the Mazda RX-7, the Nissan Skyline, the Toyota Supra, the Toyota MR-2, the Mazda MX-5 and many other vehicles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carthrottle.com/post/w92ry27/|title=All the Initial D cars specs in one post|website=Car Throttle|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\nHollywood embraced the drifting subculture in the film ''[[The Fast and the Furious: Tokyo Drift]]'' (2006).\n\n[[Paul Newman]]'s character [[Doc Hudson]], a 1951 [[Fabulous Hudson Hornet]] in ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]'' (2006), uses drifting techniques on a dirt track in the desert to demonstrate his skills to skeptical NASCAR rookie [[Lightning McQueen]].\n\nThe 2019 [[Netflix]] television series ''[[Hyperdrive (American TV series)|Hyperdrive]]'' is a [[reality competition]] show that focuses heavily on drifting.\n\n=== Computer and console gaming ===\nDrifting's popularity in computer games extends back to early arcade racers where techniques for games such as ''[[Sega Rally]]'' and ''[[Ridge Racer (video game)|Ridge Racer]]'' involved drifting. The technique is now considered mainstream in modern games in all their forms. In-game communities have developed within games such as ''[[Assetto Corsa]]'', ''[[Forza Motorsport]]'' and ''[[Gran Turismo (series)|Gran Turismo]]'', made up of teams who battle in user-created tournaments.\n\nDrifting also features heavily in the ''[[Need for Speed]]'' franchise (notably games since ''[[Need for Speed: Underground]]''), the ''[[Race Driver: Grid|Grid]]'' franchise, the ''[[Juiced (video game)|Juiced]]'' franchise and in Japanese domestic console games such as ''Initial D: Extreme Stage'' ([[PlayStation 3|PS3]]), which is based solely on drifting.\n\nDrifting and the related technique of [[powersliding]] feature heavily in the ''[[Mario Kart]]'' franchise, where a successful drift or powerslide around corners will award the player with a short [[Nitrous oxide engine|nitrous]] boost known as a \"mini-turbo\". Similar gameplay mechanics also exist in games from the ''[[Asphalt (series)|Asphalt]]'' series, where drifting and other fast-paced vehicular maneuvers are a recurring theme.\n\nBrowser-based games include the popular ''Drift Hunters'',<ref>https://www.drifted.com/drifting-games/drifted-games-drift-hunters/</ref> [[NZ Performance Car]]'s ''Drift Legends''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.driftlegends.com/ |title=Drift Legends |access-date=2008-11-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014112431/http://www.driftlegends.com/ |archive-date=2008-10-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref> (the first online game to feature real racetracks, and now ported to iPhone/iPod touch<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tone.co.nz/technology-news-4900/drift-legends-v2-drifting-game-released-on-itunes |title=Online games, technology news and reviews &#124; \u00bb Drift Legends v2 drifting game released on iTunes |publisher=Tone.co.nz |date=9 February 2011 |access-date=8 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724194927/http://www.tone.co.nz/technology-news-4900/drift-legends-v2-drifting-game-released-on-itunes |archivedate=24 July 2011 }}</ref>) and [[Mercedes-AMG]]\u2019s ''Wintersport Drift Competition''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mercedes-amg.com/webspecial/games/drift_comp/ |title=Wintersport Drift Competition |access-date=2010-02-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212224153/http://www.mercedes-amg.com/webspecial/games/drift_comp/ |archive-date=2010-02-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref> (the first manufacturer-backed drifting game). Drifting games for mobile devices are readily available from major developers and independent studios.\n\n=== Documentaries ===\n''High Performance Imports. Volume 10'' features Australian journalists from express publications, and Australian professional drifter Darren Appleton traveling to Japan, purchasing a drift vehicle (Nissan R32 GTS-T four-door), traveling with the likes of D1 champions and entering a drift event.<ref>Ellis, Ben et al. (2008), ''High Performance Imports volume 10'' (DVD), Express Motoring Publications</ref>\n\nIn 2011 Phil Morisson and James Robinson of Driftworks embarked on a journey to Japan where they would shoot a documentary about the local drifting scene, which would become known to the public as \"Outsiders\". [https://www.driftworks.com/blog/2013/11/outsiders-japan-movie-freeeeeee/]\n\n== See also ==\n{{Wikipedia books|Drifting}}\n* [[International Drift Championship Racing]]\n* [[Opposite lock]]\n* [[Tafheet]]\u2014illegal street drifting in Arab countries.\n* [[Fishtailing]]\n* [[Jackknifing]]\n* [[Scandinavian flick]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- ==============================({{NoMoreLinks}})============================== -->\n<!-- DO NOT ADD MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS -->\n<!-- If you think that your link might be useful, instead of placing it here, put -->\n<!-- it on this article's discussion page first. Links that have not been verified -->\n<!--                                WILL BE DELETED.                               -->\n<!-- ============================================================================= -->\n{{Commons category|Drifting (motorsports)}}\n\n{{Automotive handling}}\n{{Extreme sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Drifting (Motorsport)}}\n[[Category:Drifting| ]]\n[[Category:Driving techniques]]\n[[Category:Motorsport terminology]]\n[[Category:Sports originating in Japan]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Comparison between two drifting techniques.svg|thumb|A diagram showing two different drifting techniques]]\n'''Drifting''' is a [[driving]] technique where the driver intentionally [[Understeer and oversteer|oversteers]], with loss of traction, while maintaining control and driving the car through the entirety of a corner. The technique causes the rear [[slip angle]] to exceed the front slip angle to such an extent that often the front wheels are pointing in the opposite direction to the turn (e.g. car is turning left, wheels are pointed right or vice versa, also known as [[opposite lock]] or [[Countersteering#Other uses|counter-steering]]).  The sport of drifting is not to be confused with the ''four wheel drift'', a classic cornering technique established in [[Grand Prix motor racing|Grand Prix]] and sports car racing. Drifting is traditionally done by [[clutch]] kicking, then intentionally oversteering and countersteering.\n\nAs a [[Motorsport|motoring]] discipline, drifting competitions were first popularized in Japan in the 1970s and further popularized by the 1995 manga series ''[[Initial D]]''. Drifting competitions are held worldwide and are judged according to the speed, angle, showmanship and line taken through a corner or set of corners.<ref>{{cite book|last=Abdulrahim |first=M. |title=SAE Technical Paper Series |id=ITSD |chapter=On the Dynamics of Automobile Drifting |volume=1 |publisher=University of Florida |year=2006 |doi=10.4271/2006-01-1019 |citeseerx=10.1.1.103.9227 }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Origin ===\nJapan was the birthplace of drifting.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McKirdy |first1=Andrew |title=Drifting: Japan-born street sport roars onto global stage |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2017/10/04/more-sports/auto-racing/drifting-japan-born-street-sport-roars-onto-global-stage/#.W07Z9tIzaUm |website=The Japan Times |accessdate=18 July 2018 |date=October 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Banner |first1=Justin |title=The History of Drifting and The Future of Formula Drift |url=https://motoiq.com/The-History-of-Drifting-and-The-Future-of-Formula-Drift/ |website=MotoIQ |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Legendary Toyota AE86 and the Origins of Drift Racing |url=https://injapan.gaijinpot.com/uncategorized/2013/07/02/origins-of-drift-racing-legendary-toyota-ae86/ |website=GaijinPot |accessdate=18 July 2018 |date=July 2, 2013}}</ref> It was most popular in the [[Japanese Touring Car Championship|All Japan Touring Car Championship]] races. Famous [[Motorcycle sport|motorcyclist]] turned driver [[Kunimitsu Takahashi]] was the foremost creator of drifting techniques in the 1970s. This earned him several championships and a legion of fans who enjoyed the spectacle of smoking tires. The [[bias-ply]] racing tires of the 1960s&ndash;1980s lent themselves to driving styles with a high slip angle. As professional racers in Japan drove this way, so did street racers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dixon |first1=Chris |title=DRIVING; Drifting: The Fast Art of the Controlled Slide |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/05/07/travel/driving-drifting-the-fast-art-of-the-controlled-slide.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=18 July 2018 |date=May 7, 2004}}</ref>\n\n[[Keiichi Tsuchiya]], known as the {{Nihongo|\"Drift King\"|\u30c9\u30ea\u30d5\u30c8\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\n|Dorifuto Kingu}}, became particularly interested by Takahashi's drift techniques. Tsuchiya began practicing his drifting skills on the [[T\u014dge|mountain roads]] of Japan, and quickly gained a reputation amongst the racing crowd. In 1987, several popular car magazines and tuning garages agreed to produce a video of Tsuchiya's drifting skills. The video, known as ''Pluspy'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OVyxHVhNNgY|title=Keiichi Tsuchiya - Pluspy (part 1)|last=lnsania|date=6 August 2007|publisher=|access-date=29 March 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> became a hit and inspired many of the professional drifting drivers on the circuits today. In 1988, alongside [[Option (car magazine)|''Option'' magazine]] founder and [[Editing|chief editor]] Daijiro Inada, he helped to organize one of the first events specifically for drifting called the D1 Grand Prix. He has also drifted through every turn in [[Tsukuba Circuit]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n=== Popularity ===\nOne of the earliest recorded drift events outside Japan took place in 1996 at [[Willow Springs Raceway]] in [[Willow Springs, Kern County, California|Willow Springs]], [[California]], hosted by the Japanese drifting magazine and organization [[Option (car magazine)|''Option'']]. Daijiro Inada (founder of the Japanese D1 Grand Prix), the [[National Hot Rod Association|NHRA]] [[Funny Car]] [[Drag racing|drag racer]] Kenji Okazaki, and Keiichi Tsuchiya gave demonstrations in a [[Nissan 180SX]] that the magazine had brought over from Japan. Entrants included [[Rhys Millen]] and Bryan Norris.<ref>''Super Street'', Issue 4, December 1996</ref> Drifting has since exploded into a form of motorsport in North America, Australia, Asia and Europe.\n\nDrifting has evolved into a competitive sport where drivers compete (almost exclusively in rear-wheel-drive cars) to earn points from judges based on various factors. At the top levels of competition, the [[D1 Grand Prix]] in Japan pioneered the sport. Other events such as Drift Games Extreme (formally known as the IDC \u2014 Irish Drift Championship) in [[Ireland]], [[Formula D]] in the [[United States]], [[Drift Allstars]], King of Europe, Drift Masters and the [[British Drift Championship]] in Europe, [[World Drift Series|WDS]] in China, [[Russian Drift Series|RDS]] in Russia, [[Formula Drift Asia]] in the Malaysia/Singapore/Thailand/Indonesia, [[NZ Drift Series]] in New Zealand, the Australian Drifting Grand Prix, and the Greek Drift Championship (Drift Wars) have come along to further expand it into a legitimate motorsport worldwide. Drivers within these series are able to keep their cars sliding for extended periods of time, often linking several turns.\n\n== Drift competition ==\nDrifting competitions are judged based on line, angle, speed, style and show factor. Line involves taking the correct line, which is usually announced beforehand by judges. The show factor is based on many things, such as the amount of smoke, how close the car is to the wall or designated clipping point, giving the crowd's reaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YCcuUADvAfE |title=How drifting is judged |publisher=Youtube.com |date=|accessdate=2011-08-08}}</ref> The desired line is usually dictated by the judge or judges, who describe their desired line as well as highlight areas of importance, such as clipping zones, clipping points and touch-and-go areas.\n\n* Angle is the angle of a car and, more importantly, the turned wheels in a drift, speed is the speed entering a turn, the speed through a turn, and the speed exiting the turn; faster is better. Style is scored on a combination of a rate-to-angle during the initiation, how fluid the car looks through the course, and how committed the driver is through the course.\n* The rate-to-angle is how quickly during {{Nihongo|initiation|\u632f\u51fa\u3057|furidashi}} or {{Nihongo|transitions|\u632f\u66ff\u3057|furikaeshi}} a car gets to its sliding angle.\n* Fluidity is how smoothly a driver maneuvers their car around the course, taking into account the amount of correction that a driver applies through turns, and the smoothness with which the car transitions from one corner to the next.\n* Commitment is about how much throttle the driver applies, and the confidence and dedication the driver shows when approaching track edges and barriers. The higher the rate-to-angle, the more speed and angle a driver can carry through the course. In addition, the fewer corrections they apply through the course and the closer they drive to the track edges or barriers, the higher their style score.\n\n[[File:Team Drift.jpg|thumb|Team Drift Competition in [[Melbourne]]]]\nJudging takes place on just a small part of the circuit, a few linking corners that provide good viewing, and opportunities for drifting. The rest of the circuit is irrelevant, but it pertains to controlling the temperature of the tires and setting the car up for the first judged corner. In [[tandem]] passes, the lead driver (in the lead car, Senko) often feints their entry to the first corner to upset the chase driver (in the chase car, Atooi); however, in some European series, this practice is frowned upon by judges and considered foul play, resulting in deduction of points.\n\nThere are typically two sessions &ndash; a qualifying or practice session, and a final session. In qualifying sessions, referred to as {{Nihongo|\"solo runs\"|\u5358\u8d70|tans\u014d}}, drifters get individual passes in front of judges (who may or may not be the final judges) to try to make the final 16. This is often on the day preceding the final.\n\nThe finals are tandem passes called {{Nihongo|\"chases\"|\u8ffd\u8d70|tsuis\u014d}}. Drivers are paired off, and each heat comprises two passes, with each driver taking a turn to lead. The best of the eight heats go to the next four, to the next two, to the final. The passes are judged as explained above; however, there are some provisos such as:\n\n* Overtaking the lead car under drift conditions is allowed if the chasing car doesn't interrupt the lead car's drift.\n* Overtaking the lead car under grip conditions automatically forfeits a pass.\n* Spinning forfeits a pass, unless the other driver also spins.\n* Increasing the lead under drift conditions helps to win a pass.\n* Maintaining a close gap while chasing under drift conditions helps to win a pass.\n*The level of smoke from the tires is also a factor.\n\nPoints are awarded for each pass, and usually, one driver prevails. Sometimes, the judges cannot agree, or cannot decide, or a crowd vocally disagrees with the judge's decision.<ref>{{cite web|title=One More Time (OMT)|url=http://formulad.com/info/judging-info.php|website=Formula D|accessdate=15 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625122256/http://formulad.com/info/judging-info.php|archive-date=25 June 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In such cases, more passes may be run until a winner is produced. On occasion, mechanical failure determines the battle's outcome, either during or preceding a heat. If a car cannot enter a tandem battle, the remaining entrant (who automatically advances) will give a solo demonstration pass. In the event of apparently close or tied runs, crowds often demonstrate their desire for another run with chants of 'one more time'.<ref>[http://www.turbomagazine.com/features/0401tur_drifting_inaugural_d1_grand_prix/index.html Drift Mania! Inaugural D1 Grand Prix presented by Yokohama August 31, 2003], Turbo Magazine. Retrieved August 25, 2007.</ref>\n\n=== Outside of Japan ===\nThere is some regional variation. For example, in Australia, the chase car is judged on how accurately it emulates the drift of the lead car, as opposed to being judged on its own merit \u2014 this is only taken into consideration by the judges if the lead car is on the appropriate racing line.<ref>{{cite web|title=Australian Drifting Grand Prix sporting regulations, section 2.10.1 Judging Criteria - Drift Battles|url=http://australiandriftinggp.com.au/adgp101/sporting-regulations/#judgingcriteriadriftbattles|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316192732/http://australiandriftinggp.com.au/adgp101/sporting-regulations/|archivedate=16 March 2017}}</ref> Other variations of the tans\u014d/tsuis\u014d and the tans\u014d-only method is multi-car group judging, seen in [[Drift Tengoku]] videos where the four-car team is judged in groups.<ref>{{cite web|title=Australian Judging|url=http://trackbattle.com.au/adgp/events/judging/|website=Track Battle|accessdate=15 July 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715202037/http://trackbattle.com.au/adgp/events/judging/|archivedate=15 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe D1GP drift series has been prototyping and fine-tuning an electronic judging system based on custom sensors that record and transmit car data to a computer that judges the run. This system is also being tested in some European series. It is designed to remove subjectivity and/or predisposition of judges. Usually the track for such a system is broken up into several sections (usually three) and the system automatically generates scores based on speed, angle and fluidity of the driver in each section, combining the scores for the final score. In certain situations judges can change or overrule a score, which happens, though rarely.\n\nFormula Drift is the top United States Drifting series. Its judging style for competition is based on line, angle, and speed. When judging for line the driver is judged based on their ability to stay on the line set in place by the judges. Points are allocated to outside zones and inner clips, and are also allocated to touch and go areas. Angle is the drivers ability to maintain a high level of angle that will be set by the angle judge in the drivers meeting. Style is judges based on three areas of focus; initiation, fluidity, and commitment. Initiation is based on how early and smooth the driver initiates into a drift. Fluidity is how smooth the driver drives from lock to lock, high angles of drift, and just overall smoothness on the track. Commitment is judges on consistent throttle throughout, and how close the driver is willing to get to walls and clipping points.<ref>http://static.formulad.com/docs/2017/2017%20Formula%20Drift%20Pro%20Sporting%20Regulations%20Version%201.0.pdf</ref>\n\nThe King of Europe Drift ProSeries has developed its own [[telemetry]] system, which uses GPS data to accurately measure speed, angle and line, thus leading to a very objective result for the qualifying sessions.<ref>Jefferies, Bill (July 11, 2014). [http://www.wanganwarriors.com/king-of-europe-battle-for-the-throne/ \"KING OF EUROPE: BATTLE FOR THE THRONE\"]. Wangan Warriors. Retrieved July 26, 2019.</ref>\n\n== Drift cars ==\n[[File:King of Europe Round 3 Lydden Hill 2014 (14356011899).jpg|thumb|Steve Moore drifting his [[Nissan Silvia]] (S14) around Lydden Hill at King of Europe Round 3 (2014)]]\n\nDrift cars are usually light- to moderate-weight rear-wheel-drive coupes and sedans, offering a large range of power levels. There have also been [[all-wheel drive]] cars that have been converted to rear-wheel drive such as the [[Subaru Impreza|Subaru WRX]], [[Toyota Avensis]], [[Scion tC]], [[Mitsubishi Lancer Evolution]] and [[Nissan GT-R]]. Early on, AWD cars without conversion were allowed in some drifting competitions, and usually the rules allowed only a certain percentage of power to be sent to the front wheels, but they are banned in most (if not all) drifting competitions today.\n\nDespite the possibility of obtaining desirable [[Japanese domestic market]] vehicles in continents outside Japan,<ref>Savage, J. (2010), \"Tuner Cars\", Edge Books</ref> drifters in other countries prefer to use local versions of the same cars (for example, a [[Nissan 240SX]] instead of a [[Nissan Silvia|Nissan Silvia S13]], etc), or even [[Domestic market|domestic cars]]. A high volume of Japanese imports were brought to countries such as Australia and New Zealand, however it is not unusual to see Australian/New Zealand domestic vehicles such as the [[Holden]] [[Holden Commodore|Commodore]] or [[Ford Motor Company of Australia|Ford]] [[Ford Falcon (Australia)|Falcon]] used in drifting competitions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zercustoms.com/news/Ford-Typhoon-Drifting-Car-2.php |title=Ford Typhoon Drifting Car - Page 2 |publisher=[[ZerCustoms]] |date=2006-09-19 |access-date=8 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111010113712/http://www.zercustoms.com/news/Ford-Typhoon-Drifting-Car-2.php |archive-date=10 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe American market saw a relatively high volume of JDM cars being imported over the last decade, despite Japanese domestic vehicles being right-hand-drive only.<ref>Alvendia, A. (2006), \"Drifting Sideways: From Japan To America\", Motorbooks</ref> Locally-sold imports such as the [[Lexus SC]] and Nissan 240SX feature heavily in American drifting, but they are usually modified with JDM engines to mirror their Japanese domestic equivalents (usually with a [[Toyota JZ engine|Toyota JZ-GTE]] or Nissan CA18DET/SR20DET/RB26DETT respectively).<ref>Schuette, S \u201cDrift Cars\u201d, Capstone Press, 2007</ref>\n\nIn the UK, there are a high level of Japanese imports used within the drifting scene, due in part to the UK sharing a right-hand drive layout with Japan. However, these cars often cost more than UK-market cars, partly due to import costs. There are plenty of UK and European models used as drift cars as well \u2014 older BMWs are particularly prominent due to cost and availability, with Volvo 300 series and Ford Sierras also proving popular.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.driftworks.com/drifting/|title=What is Drifting?|author=|date=|work=DriftWorks.com|access-date=29 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trampdrift.eu/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=51&Itemid=60|title=Article on Trampdrift - What to buy|author=|date=|work=Trampdrift.eu|access-date=29 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the Formula Drift Professional series, cars range from highly tuned Japanese automobiles reflecting the original styles of drifting to all-new age makes and models. Due to no power limit restrictions in the series, it is not uncommon for competitors to use a variety of different powerplants. Popular variations of Chevrolet [[LS based GM small-block engine|LS engines]] are often seen bolted down to Japanese frames.<ref>Chen, L \u201cHorsepower Wars\u201d, Speed Hunters, 2015</ref>\n\nIn the King of Europe Drift Series, the main professional drift series in Europe, BMW models have long ruled the scene, winning event after event, year after year. The most successful models include the [[E30 M3|E30]], [[E36 M3|E36]] and [[E46 M3|E46]], which also present an advantage in cost (being more affordable than their Japanese rivals). For a few years, BMW V8 engine swaps were the most popular, providing a healthy 300 to 400 horsepower output. With the continuous evolution of the sport, however, these have now become obsolete, making way for more powerful American V8 engines or classic Toyota 2JZ-GTE engines.\n\nAs an example, the top 15 cars in the 2003 D1GP,<ref name=\"db1\">{{cite book|title=Drift Battle 1|last=Ellis|first=Ben|publisher=Express Motoring Publications|year=2004|page=24|display-authors=etal}}</ref> top 10 in the 2004 D1GP,<ref name=\"db4\">{{cite book|title=Drift Battle 4|last=Ellis|first=Ben|publisher=Express Motoring Publications|year=2004|page=22|display-authors=etal}}</ref> and top 10 in the 2005 D1GP<ref name=\"db12\">{{cite book|title=Drift Battle 12|last=Ellis|first=Ben|publisher=Express Motoring Publications|year=2005|page=77|display-authors=etal}}\n</ref> were as follows:\n\n[[File:D1NZ07072007.jpg|thumb|Nissan Silvia S15 drifting]]\n<!--Do not edit the information in the table below. It is derived from the printed sources listed above. Add new/additional information elsewhere.-->\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Car !! Model !! 2003 !! 2004 !! 2005\n|-\n| [[Nissan Silvia]] || S15 || 6 cars || 5 cars || 3 cars\n|-\n| [[Toyota AE86|Toyota Levin/Trueno]] || AE86 || 3 cars || 3 cars || 2 cars\n|-\n| [[Mazda RX-7]] || FD3S || 2 cars || 1 car || 2 cars\n|-\n| [[Nissan Skyline]] || R34 || 1 car || 1 car || 1 car\n|-\n| Nissan Silvia || S13 || 5 cars ||   ||\n|-\n| [[Toyota Chaser]] || JZX100 || 1 car ||   ||\n|-\n| [[Subaru Impreza]] || GD (RWD) ||   ||   || 1 car\n|-\n| [[Toyota Altezza]] || SXE10 ||   ||   || 1 car\n|}\n\nThe top cars in the Red Bull Drifting Championship were as follows:<ref>[[Red Bull Drifting World Championship]] (2008)</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Driver !! Make !! Model\n|-\n|[[Tanner Foust]] || [[Nissan]] || [[Nissan 350Z|350Z]]\n|-\n|[[Ken Gushi]] || [[Scion (automobile)|Scion]] || [[Scion tC|tC]]\n|- \n|[[Kevin Huynh]] || [[Dodge]] || [[Dodge Viper|Viper]]\n|-\n|[[Rhys Millen]] || [[Pontiac]] || [[Pontiac Solstice|Solstice GXP]]\n|-\n|[[Samuel H\u00fcbinette]] || [[Dodge]] || [[Dodge Charger (LX)|Charger]]\n|-\n|[[Chris Forsberg]] || [[Nissan]] || [[Nissan 370Z|370Z]]\n|-\n|}\n\nAs for 2017, the top cars participating in [[Formula Drift]] are the [[Nissan]] [[Nissan 370Z|370Z]], Nissan [[Nissan Silvia|Silvia]] S14, Nissan Silvia S15, [[Toyota]] [[Toyota 86|86]], [[BMW]] E46, [[Ford]] Mustang, and the [[Mazda]] [[Mazda MX-5|MX-5.]]\n\n== Drift tuning ==\n\n=== Drivetrain ===\nA mechanical [[limited slip differential]] (LSD) is considered essential for drifting. Drifting with an open or viscous differential in a sustained slide generally yields relatively less impressive results. All other modifications are secondary to the LSD.<ref name=\"topsecret\">{{cite book | first = Ben | last = Ellis | year = 2004 | pages = 53\u201356 | title = Drift Battle 1 | publisher = Express Motoring Publications | quote = It might surprise some people to see this listed first, but a proper mechanical limited-slip diff is absolutely essential for drift.|display-authors=etal}}\n</ref>\n\nThe preferred form of LSD for drifting is the clutch type, in \"two-way\" form, for its consistent and aggressive lockup behavior under both acceleration and deceleration. Some drift cars use a spool \"differential\", which actually has no differential action at all \u2014 the wheels are locked to each other. Drifters on a budget may use a [[welding|welded]] differential, where the [[differential (mechanics)|side gears]] are welded to give the same effect as a spool. This makes it easier to break rear traction, because it reduces maximum traction in all situations except traveling in a straight line. Welded differentials have an inherent risk involved: due to the tremendous amount of internal stress, the welds may fail and the differential completely lock up leaving the rear wheels immobilized. Helical torque-sensing differentials such as the [[Torsen]] or [[Quaife]] (available on cars in certain stock trims such as the [[Nissan Silvia|S15]], [[Mazda RX-7|FD3S]], [[Mazda MX-5|MX-5]], [[Toyota Supra|JZA80]], and [[Toyota Soarer|UZZ3x]]) are also adequate. It is common for drifters to change the final gear ratio depending on the type of track layout.\n\nThe [[clutch]]es on drift cars tend to be very tough ceramic-brass button or multiple-plate varieties for durability, as well as to allow rapid \"clutch kick\" techniques to upset the grip of the rear wheels. Gearbox and engine mounts are often replaced with [[polyurethane|urethane]] or aluminum mounts, and dampers are added to control the violent motion of the engine and gearbox under these conditions. The driveshafts are often replaced with carbon fiber drive shafts, as they offer the highest rotational mass savings, are stronger than alternative metals, and flexible enough to absorb and dissipate vibrations, thus easing the load on the gearbox as well as the rest of the drivetrain.\n\nGear sets may be replaced with [[Close-ratio transmission|closer ratios]] to keep the engine in the [[power band]], or, on some cars that produce enough power and torque to four-gear transmissions similar to the ones used in NASCAR (such as the Andrews four-speed dog box that [[Vaughn Gittin |Vaughn Gittin Jr.]] ran in his 2016 Mustang<ref>[https://media.ford.com/content/dam/fordmedia/North%20America/US/Events/15%20SEMA/mustang_sema_sheet_09.pdf mustang_sema_sheet_09.pdf]</ref>) with more open-ratio gears, this limits the number of shifts the driver has to do during their run. These may be coarser dog engagement [[Spur gears|straight cut]] gears instead of [[Syncromesh|synchronised]] [[gear#Helical gears|helical gears]], for durability and faster shifting at the expense of noise and refinement. Wealthier drifters may use [[Sequential manual gearbox|sequential gearboxes]] to make gear selection easier and faster, while sequential shift lever adapters can be used to make shifts easier without increasing shift time.\n\n=== Steering and suspension ===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2017}}Steering angles are also crucial as the driver progresses. The first stage of these modifications is usually a modified steering knuckle or upright. Extended control arms can be employed on [[MacPherson strut]] vehicles like the Nissan S-Chassis to allow for more clearance for higher steering angles. Many aftermarket companies have developed full lock kits including modification of the vehicle's original [[scrub radius]], [[Kingpin (automotive part)|kingpin]] axis, [[Ackermann steering geometry|Ackermann angle]], amount of [[bump steer]], [[caster angle]], and kinematics as to maximize front grip and eliminate mechanical bind at steering angles in excess of 60\u00b0. While MacPherson strut vehicles are prevalent in professional drifting, [[double wishbone suspension]] vehicles can also be competitive, with often better caster and camber curves.\n\nSprings and [[shock absorber]]s are also tuned for higher skill levels, depending on track layout.\n\nTypically, dedicated drifting cars are modified to eliminate [[Ackermann steering geometry]], which is included on almost all production cars. While Ackermann geometry is helpful in making a car turn easier, it inhibits the ability to slide sideways at full lock necessary to compete in drifting.\n\n=== Cockpit ===\n[[File:Drift Carnage.jpg|thumb|right|Cleaning up severed bumpers during drift meet]]\nBecause of the high [[centrifugal force]]s encountered during drifting, drivers are usually retained by a [[bucket seat|racing seat]] and [[five-point harness]]. This allows the hands to merely turn the wheel, instead of bracing the body in the seat. The same applies for the feet, which are free to move rapidly between [[Automobile pedal|clutch, brake and accelerator pedals]]. The [[steering wheel]] is usually relatively small, dished, and perfectly round, so that it can be released and allowed to spin in the driver's hands as the caster returns the front wheels to center. The locking knob on the [[hand brake]] is usually replaced with a spin turn knob; this stops the hand brake locking on when pulled. Nearly all drivers move the hand brake location or add an extra hydraulic hand brake actuator for greater braking force. Additional gauges are used to monitor [[Boost gauge|boost levels]], [[oil pressure]] and temperature, intake and [[Engine coolant temperature sensor|coolant temperatures]], and [[Air\u2013fuel ratio|air-fuel ratio]], among other data. Some drivers, especially in larger cars, move the seating position for a better weight distribution, such as [[Daigo Saito]] and his 2014 JZX100 Mk.II Chaser.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://noriyaro.com/2014/10/speed-holes-and-methanol-daigo-saitos-2014-jzx100/|title=SPEED HOLES AND METHANOL: Daigo Saito's 2014 JZX100 : NORIYARO|author=|date=|work=noriyaro.com|accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Tires ===\n[[File:Drift s13 wheel.jpg|thumb|upright|S13 Silvia - tire stretched over a wide rim, increasing sidewall rigidity. The rim has a low offset to increase track.]]\nIn the United States, competitive drifters are required to run US [[Department of transportation|DOT]]-approved (road-legal) tires similar to [[racing slick]]s in rubber composition, but with shallow treads included. This is permitted, with the exception of some major championships including D1GP and Formula Drift, which only permit commercially available tires that are approved by the sanctioning body. Professional drifting has come to the point where grip is tuned into cars to be defeated. It makes for a faster drift necessary in the current professional climate. Tires typically used by drifters are around the DOT tread wear rating of 200. Examples include the Hankook Ventus RS-3, Falken Azenis RT615K, Nitto NT05, Yokohama ADVAN Neova AD08R, and Achilles Radial 123s. Some other companies from Asia have also started developing their technology through sponsoring professional drivers. These companies include Nankang,<ref>[http://www.wreckedmagazine.com/blog/2014/12/08/nankang-tire-set-for-2015-formula-drift-arrival-rumormill/]</ref> Westlake<ref>[http://www.drifting.cz/calendar/race?slug=rd6-westlake-drift-challenge-sosnova]</ref> and Zestino.<ref>[http://www.thebritishdriftchampionship.co.uk/2017/02/28/zestino-tires-uk-partner-british-drift-championship/]</ref> Tires are often modified with [[Tire lettering|lettering]] to give them a more customized look.\n\n== R/C drifting ==\n{{Main|Radio-controlled drifting}}\nR/C drifting refers to the act of drifting with a [[radio-controlled car]]. R/C cars are equipped with special low-grip tires, usually made from [[PVC]] or ABS piping. Some manufacturers make radial drift tires that are made of actual rubber compounds. The car's setup is usually changed to allow it to drift more easily. R/C drifting is most successful on AWD R/C cars. Companies such as Overdose, [[Yokomo]], MST, [[Tamiya Corporation|Tamiya]], [[Team Associated]], and Hobby Products International<ref>[http://www.hpieurope.com/tv13/?channel=9&src=wikipedia HPI R/C Drift Videos] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726073449/http://www.hpieurope.com/tv13/?channel=9&src=wikipedia |date=July 26, 2011 }} and [http://www.hpieurope.com/walk.php?lang=en&id=19 Guide to R/C drifting] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726073454/http://www.hpieurope.com/walk.php?lang=en&id=19 |date=July 26, 2011 }}</ref> have made dedicated drift cars and supported the hobby.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tamiya.com/english/products/58386silvia_tt01d/index.htm |title=1/10 R/C Nismo Coppermix Silvia \uff08TT-01D\uff09 Drift Spec |publisher=Tamiya.com |date=2007-03-08 |accessdate=2011-08-08}}</ref>\n\n== In the media ==\n\n=== Film and television ===\nOne of the key sources responsible for the international spread of drifting is the Japanese manga and anime series ''[[Initial D]]'', which features [[List of Initial D characters#Takumi Fujiwara|Takumi Fujiwara]], a high school student who learns to drift on the Mt. Akina [[t\u014dge]] (mountain pass) using a custom [[Toyota AE86]]. The series features a large number of Japanese performance vehicles, including the Mazda RX-7, the Nissan Skyline, the Toyota Supra, the Toyota MR-2, the Mazda MX-5 and many other vehicles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carthrottle.com/post/w92ry27/|title=All the Initial D cars specs in one post|website=Car Throttle|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\nHollywood embraced the drifting subculture in the film ''[[The Fast and the Furious: Tokyo Drift]]'' (2006).\n\n[[Paul Newman]]'s character [[Doc Hudson]], a 1951 [[Fabulous Hudson Hornet]] in ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]'' (2006), uses drifting techniques on a dirt track in the desert to demonstrate his skills to skeptical NASCAR rookie [[Lightning McQueen]].\n\nThe 2019 [[Netflix]] television series ''[[Hyperdrive (American TV series)|Hyperdrive]]'' is a [[reality competition]] show that focuses heavily on drifting.\n\n=== Computer and console gaming ===\nDrifting\u2019s popularity in computer games extends back to early arcade racers where techniques for games such as ''[[Sega Rally]]'' and ''[[Ridge Racer (video game)|Ridge Racer]]'' involved drifting. The technique is now considered mainstream in modern games in all their forms. In-game communities have developed within games such as ''[[Assetto Corsa]]'', ''[[Forza Motorsport]]'' and ''[[Gran Turismo (series)|Gran Turismo]]'', made up of teams who battle in user-created tournaments.\n\nDrifting also features heavily in the ''[[Need for Speed]]'' franchise (notably games since ''[[Need for Speed: Underground]]''), the ''[[Race Driver: Grid|Grid]]'' franchise, the ''[[Juiced (video game)|Juiced]]'' franchise and in Japanese domestic console games such as ''Initial D: Extreme Stage'' ([[PlayStation 3|PS3]]), which is based solely on drifting.\n\nDrifting and the related technique of [[powersliding]] feature heavily in the ''[[Mario Kart]]'' franchise, where a successful drift or powerslide around corners will award the player with a short [[Nitrous oxide engine|nitrous]] boost known as a \"mini-turbo\". Similar gameplay mechanics also exist in games from the ''[[Asphalt (series)|Asphalt]]'' series, where drifting and other fast-paced vehicular maneuvers are a recurring theme.\n\nBrowser-based games include the popular ''Drift Hunters'',<ref>https://www.drifted.com/drifting-games/drifted-games-drift-hunters/</ref> [[NZ Performance Car]]'s ''Drift Legends''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.driftlegends.com/ |title=Drift Legends |access-date=2008-11-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014112431/http://www.driftlegends.com/ |archive-date=2008-10-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref> (the first online game to feature real racetracks, and now ported to iPhone/iPod touch<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tone.co.nz/technology-news-4900/drift-legends-v2-drifting-game-released-on-itunes |title=Online games, technology news and reviews &#124; \u00bb Drift Legends v2 drifting game released on iTunes |publisher=Tone.co.nz |date=9 February 2011 |access-date=8 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724194927/http://www.tone.co.nz/technology-news-4900/drift-legends-v2-drifting-game-released-on-itunes |archivedate=24 July 2011 }}</ref>) and [[Mercedes-AMG]]\u2019s ''Wintersport Drift Competition''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mercedes-amg.com/webspecial/games/drift_comp/ |title=Wintersport Drift Competition |access-date=2010-02-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212224153/http://www.mercedes-amg.com/webspecial/games/drift_comp/ |archive-date=2010-02-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref> (the first manufacturer-backed drifting game). Drifting games for mobile devices are readily available from major developers and independent studios.\n\n=== Documentaries ===\n''High Performance Imports. Volume 10'' features Australian journalists from express publications, and Australian professional drifter Darren Appleton traveling to Japan, purchasing a drift vehicle (Nissan R32 GTS-T four-door), traveling with the likes of D1 champions and entering a drift event.<ref>Ellis, Ben et al. (2008), ''High Performance Imports volume 10'' (DVD), Express Motoring Publications</ref>\n\nIn 2011 Phil Morisson and James Robinson of Driftworks embarked on a journey to Japan where they would shoot a documentary about the local drifting scene, which would become known to the public as \"Outsiders\". [https://www.driftworks.com/blog/2013/11/outsiders-japan-movie-freeeeeee/]\n\n== See also ==\n{{Wikipedia books|Drifting}}\n* [[International Drift Championship Racing]]\n* [[Opposite lock]]\n* [[Tafheet]]\u2014illegal street drifting in Arab countries.\n* [[Fishtailing]]\n* [[Jackknifing]]\n* [[Scandinavian flick]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- ==============================({{NoMoreLinks}})============================== -->\n<!-- DO NOT ADD MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS -->\n<!-- If you think that your link might be useful, instead of placing it here, put -->\n<!-- it on this article's discussion page first. Links that have not been verified -->\n<!--                                WILL BE DELETED.                               -->\n<!-- ============================================================================= -->\n{{Commons category|Drifting (motorsports)}}\n\n{{