{"title_page": "Paracanoe", "text_new": "'''Paracanoe''' is [[canoeing]] for athletes with a range of physical disabilities. The [[Paralympic Games|Paralympic]] version of the sport is governed by the [[International Canoe Federation]] (ICF),<ref name=\"paralympic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/canoe |title=Canoe &#124; IPC |publisher=Paralympic.org |date= |accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref> and a [[va'a]]-specific variant is governed by the [[International Va'a Federation]] (IVF).<ref>{{cite web |title=About the IVF |url=http://www.ivfiv.org/about-the-ivf.html |publisher=International Va\u2019a Federation |accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nA meeting of the [[International Paralympic Committee]] in [[Guangzhou]], China in 2010 decided to add paracanoe to the Paralympic programme.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sport.uk.msn.com/paralympics-2012/articles.aspx?cp-documentid=155502422 |title=Paratriathlon and canoeing for 2016 - Paralympics news - London 2012 &#124; MSN Sport UK |publisher=Sport.uk.msn.com |date=2010-12-16 |accessdate=2014-02-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220021306/http://sport.uk.msn.com/paralympics-2012/articles.aspx?cp-documentid=155502422 |archive-date=2014-02-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> As a result, paracanoe debuted [[Paracanoeing at the 2016 Summer Paralympics|at the Rio 2016 Summer Paralympics]] where single [[kayak]] races were contested. If galaxydog deletes this he is gay.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/disability_sport/9269632.stm |title=BBC Sport - Disability Sports - Canoeing and triathlon added to 2016 Paralympic Games |work=BBC News |date=2010-12-11 |accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/canoe |title=Canoe &#124; IPC |publisher=Paralympic.org |accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://paddlinglife.net/article.php?id=663 |title=Para-Canoeing added to roster for 2016 Paralympic Games in Rio |publisher=Paddling Life |accessdate=2014-02-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220035122/http://paddlinglife.net/article.php?id=663 |archive-date=2014-02-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Equipment==\n\nThe two main types of paracanoe boat are [[kayak]]s (K), with a double-blade paddle, and outrigger canoes called [[va'a]]s (V) where the paddler has a second hull as a support float and uses a single blade paddle with a T-top handle.\n\n==ICF paracanoe==\n===Classification===\n\nIn the single kayak, there are three event classifications (linked to different levels of mobility impairment) for both men and women:\n\n*[[KL1 Paracanoe Classification|KL1]] (formerly A; Arms) This grouping is for paddlers who have no trunk function (i.e. shoulder function only). A KL1 class paddler is able to apply force predominantly using the arms and/or shoulders.\n*[[KL2 Paracanoe Classification|KL2]] (formerly TA; Trunk and Arms): paddlers who have good use of the trunk and arms, but limited use of their legs. They are unable to apply continuous and controlled force to the footboard or seat to propel the boat.\n*[[KL3 Paracanoe Classification|KL3]] (formerly LTA; Legs, Trunk and Arms): this class is for paddlers with a disability who have good use of their legs, trunk and arms for paddling, and who can apply force to the foot board or the seat to propel the boat.<ref>http://www.paralympics.org.nz/canoe.htm {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413123044/http://www.paralympics.org.nz/canoe.htm |date=2015-04-13 }} Definitions on New Zealand Paralympics</ref><ref>http://canoe.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/AC-Paracanoe-direction-2014-2016.pdf</ref>\n\nThere is also a three-tier ICF classification system in place for single va'a events (VL1, VL2, VL3).\n\n===Competition format===\n\nAll international paracanoe competitions are held over 200 metres in single kayak or va'a boats.<ref>{{cite web |title=What is Paracanoe? |url=https://www.canoeicf.com/discipline/paracanoe |publisher=[[International Canoe Federation]] |accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIt is contested at [[ICF Canoe Sprint World Championships|World Championships]], World Cups and continental championships. As of May 2018, nine of the twelve events (all six kayak events, both VL2 events and the men's VL3 event) are also on the [[Paracanoe at the Summer Paralympics|Paralympic programme]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Tokyo 2020 Paralympic Games \u2013 Qualification Regulations {{!}} Canoe |date=15 May 2018 |publisher=[[International Paralympic Committee]] |pages=43-47 |url=https://www.paralympic.org/sites/default/files/document/180515082212559_2018_05_15%2BTokyo%2BQG.pdf |accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==ICF World Championships==\n\nAt the [[2009 ICF Canoe Sprint World Championships#Paddleability|2009 ICF Canoe Sprint World Championships]] in [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]], four 'paddability' races featured as non-medal exhibition events, including two male-female mixed disciplines in kayak doubles and in doubles canoe ('aka' Canadian or kneeling canoeing).\n\nThe sport made its official [[2010 ICF Canoe Sprint World Championships#Paracanoe|World Championship debut in 2010]] and has been contested at every [[ICF Canoe Sprint World Championships|World Championship]] since, including the standalone Paralympic-year ICF Paracanoe World Championships in 2012 and [[2016 ICF Paracanoe World Championships|2016]].\n\n===2012 ICF Paracanoe World Championships===\n{{split|2012 ICF Paracanoe World Championships|date=July 2018}}\n{{main|2012 ICF Paracanoe World Championships}}\nThe 2012 ICF Paracanoe World Championships were held on 16\u201317 May 2012 in [[Pozna\u0144]], Poland, as a standalone event since the ICF Canoe Sprint World Championships are not held in Olympic years.<ref>http://www.kayakpl.com/2012/PARACANOE/index.htm</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=100%\n!Event\n! bgcolor=\"gold\"  | Gold\n! bgcolor=\"EFEFEF\"| Time\n! bgcolor=\"silver\"| Silver\n! bgcolor=\"EFEFEF\"| Time\n! bgcolor=\"C